uccessfully, to foment a revolution. Exiled to America with his wife and children, Ed never gave up hope that Burma would one day adopt a new democratic government. Though he died disappointed, he left in his daughter's care an illuminating trove of papers documenting the experiences of an eccentric, ambitious, humorous, and determined patriot, vividly recounting the realities of colonial rule, Japanese occupation, postwar reconstruction, and military dictatorship. This memoir tells the twin histories of Law-Yone's kin and his country, a nation whose vicissitudes continue to intrigue the world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aBiography & AutobiographyxPolitical. 0aImmigrantszGreat BritainvBiography. 0aKaren (Southeast Asian people)xBurmaxSocial conditions. 0aNewspaper editorsxBurmavBiography. 0aNewspaper editorszBurmavBiography. 0aNewspaper publishingxBurmaxHistoryy20th century. 0aNewspaper publishingzBurmaxHistoryy20th century. 0aPhan, ZoyaxChildhood and youth. 0aSocial SciencexEssays. 0aSocial SciencexReference. 0aWomen immigrantszGreat BritainvBiography. 7aHISTORY / Asia / India & South Asia.2bisacsh1 aSteinberg, David.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagez978311064977208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311066586440uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/lawy1693640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231537803423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780231537803.jpg  a978-3-11-064977-2  Asian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagec2000d2014  a978-3-11-066586-4  Columbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL